00:39:01.850 --> 00:39:21.439
Greg K | Lido: Okay, nice. So, I will try to keep it short, because this EIP was also discussed by Dima in a previous ACD call, just to, like, recap everything. So, it's EIP-8148, Custom Sweep Threshold for validators. It was also by Dima, Dmitri, and myself, who are all Lido contributors.

235
00:39:21.440 --> 00:39:24.839
Greg K | Lido: And, it has to do with,

236
00:39:24.840 --> 00:39:44.770
Greg K | Lido: the proof-of-stake, withdrawal credentials for validators. So, yeah, like, I think here for ACD call, we don't really need much background, but just as a reminder, what's the difference is, like, you have two validators, Alice and Bob, 01 and 02. The difference is that, when you, like, your effective balance exceeds 32 ETH,

237
00:39:44.770 --> 00:40:00.969
Greg K | Lido: The 0x01 validators, the legacy ones, the rewards are automatically withdrawn every roughly one week from the automatic withdrawal algorithm, while 0x02 validators, this is not happening, the balance is compounding.

238
00:40:01.620 --> 00:40:24.060
Greg K | Lido: And, actually, the new threshold for 002 validators is 2048 ETH. So, there is this kind of asymmetry between 32 and, 2048, and nothing in between. So, yeah, fast comparison, like we all know, 002 validators can accumulate balance, while 001 cannot. They have both

239
00:40:24.060 --> 00:40:26.679
Greg K | Lido: Minimum and maximum on 32 degrees.

240
00:40:27.500 --> 00:40:37.150
Greg K | Lido: 002 validators require almost the same hardware resources per validator, but the important thing here is, like, 002 validators

241
00:40:37.150 --> 00:40:47.600
Greg K | Lido: are better for the network, particularly to reduce total validator count. It was one of the main incentives to introduce in this class. And essentially, for fast finality, which is one of the most important parts of the

242
00:40:47.600 --> 00:41:07.190
Greg K | Lido: future, roadmap, requires from 10x to 30x decrease on the number of validators to enable fast finality, together with other strawmap, elements. So, this is really where we need to go, and this is why, the goal of the protocol is to have validators switching to 002,

243
00:41:07.190 --> 00:41:26.259
Greg K | Lido: However, the main problem is that the adoption of this is slower than expected, although over the last few months, we had some improvements. So currently, I said this morning, this, from Bhuta, from June, like, 1.5% of validators are 002, and they hold roughly

244
00:41:26.260 --> 00:41:33.390
Greg K | Lido: 28% of all is staked, because they have average of 821.

245
00:41:33.430 --> 00:41:47.909
Greg K | Lido: And it has been quite discussed why is this adoption slow, and why people are not moving to 002, and one of the reasons is the liquidity concern. It's exactly this part that you don't get

246
00:41:47.910 --> 00:41:55.789
Greg K | Lido: regular reward distribution with this automatic reward scheming as, in 001 case, that whatever goes

247
00:41:56.280 --> 00:42:04.159
Greg K | Lido: above 32 ETH, you receive immediately, with no single actions required from the, like, from the validator.

248
00:42:04.160 --> 00:42:18.370
Greg K | Lido: And actually, that was the initial motivation of, the EIP, like, it was, like, during discussions in, Buenos Aires, like, in Devon last year, that this seems to be one of the big, barriers for many people to enter, 002.

249
00:42:20.080 --> 00:42:31.820
Greg K | Lido: And, yeah, example of people that, were saying the same thing were, like, some small solo stakers, like, just 32 each stakers that they say, okay, I prefer to have this predictable

250
00:42:31.820 --> 00:42:56.150
Greg K | Lido: has free rewards coming to me, and, but we had also serious, similar, cases with people who run, like, like, bigger, like, 6 validators, but… and the question is, like, why should I convert my 6 validators to 1 if I don't get my rewards automatically? Because I'm too far from the 2048 ETH. And similarly, there are also bigger players with just less than this, amount of ETH.

251
00:42:56.150 --> 00:43:11.450
Greg K | Lido: but they also prefer to receive the rewards automatically. And also, another class is fractional home stakers, like the ones that are using permissionless staking pools, like the CSM or ReptPool, that, they cannot afford

252
00:43:11.450 --> 00:43:29.749
Greg K | Lido: bonds for full 002 keys, but so they prefer to stay 001 in order to be able to afford the bond and receive the rewards, for free, basically. So the solution, as you might predict, is to introduce a custom sweep threshold. So, instead of having

253
00:43:30.080 --> 00:43:33.870
Greg K | Lido: the sweep threshold fixed at 2048 ETH.

254
00:43:33.990 --> 00:43:46.070
Greg K | Lido: just make this a configurable constant for every 002 validator. So this is now… it would not be a universal constant, it will be just separate value for its validator, and when

255
00:43:46.070 --> 00:43:54.959
Greg K | Lido: The effective balance goes above the stress code, then the rewards will be sent automatically to the execution layer with raw credentials.

256
00:43:55.570 --> 00:44:01.579
Greg K | Lido: So this achieves best of both worlds for this class of validators we've discussed, because

257
00:44:01.610 --> 00:44:18.829
Greg K | Lido: they can set any desired amount of ETH to accumulate, so it's quite continuous, between 32 and 2048 ETH, depending on the profile of the validator. They receive any excess rewards automatically, and they can also change the threshold at any time.

258
00:44:19.080 --> 00:44:35.200
Greg K | Lido: In terms of security, and, kind of protocol properties, it's designed in a way that it does not allow withdrawal gaming, so you cannot set the new threshold to be below your current balance, so it cannot be used as an excuse

259
00:44:35.200 --> 00:44:41.580
Greg K | Lido: to have faster withdrawals. So every validator, like, let's say if someone

260
00:44:41.580 --> 00:44:49.120
Greg K | Lido: today has a thousand ETH, they cannot set the custom threshold below this, they cannot set above it.

261
00:44:49.120 --> 00:45:10.860
Greg K | Lido: And the full control of the, of this threshold is to the stakeholder, so, it's only via execution layer triggerable actions that are introduced in Pectra, so the entity that contains… that owns the ETH, not the entity who runs the validator, can, can only change this script threshold.

262
00:45:11.200 --> 00:45:30.200
Greg K | Lido: So, just to wrap up, what are the main benefits? First of all, for Ethereum protocol, the main benefit is that we expect that this will help reducing the validator count, which in turn enables fast finality, while not putting the smallest validators at this advantage.

263
00:45:30.510 --> 00:45:47.560
Greg K | Lido: And a second interesting feature that I think it's quite useful for the future of Ethereum Protocol is that this makes a potential future change of max effective balance, or even complete removal of max effective balance much easier.

264
00:45:47.560 --> 00:45:54.919
Greg K | Lido: Because, currently, the way that the protocol is, in order to remove the maximum effective balance, you need to…

265
00:45:55.420 --> 00:46:14.269
Greg K | Lido: modify also this sweep withdrawal algorithm. They interact quite heavily, but now, like with EIP-8148, this current constant of 2048 could be just used as the custom ceiling for current 002 validator. So, I think in the later part of the strawmap, there is an item which is called

266
00:46:14.270 --> 00:46:20.809
Greg K | Lido: the preset, and it includes also, as far as I understand, removing the max EB, and I think this EIP

267
00:46:21.010 --> 00:46:28.170
Greg K | Lido: prepare the ground quite easily to make this future change much smoother, and which I think it's a good change for the Ethereum Proof of Stake.

268
00:46:28.250 --> 00:46:41.710
Greg K | Lido: For validators, it allows flexibility, because a validator can become 002 and receive rewards at any desired threshold, so there are no kind of incentives to remain in 001, or trade-offs.

269
00:46:41.710 --> 00:46:48.890
Greg K | Lido: And small stakers and fractional home stakers can remain into the game, without being at disadvantage.

270
00:46:49.370 --> 00:47:14.350
Greg K | Lido: And one might ask, like, why, whether there is some impact on light as well. So, there will be some impact, but it's quite, small, and I just wanted to emphasize this. Like, 95% of Lido validators will switch to 002 anyways, no matter what happens with this EIP. You know, permissions, we already start the test network

271
00:47:14.350 --> 00:47:17.370
Greg K | Lido: migrations and, should be shipped until Q1.

272
00:47:17.370 --> 00:47:26.390
Greg K | Lido: next year. And also, CSM, like, permissionless module for 002 validators will be, set by end of this year.

273
00:47:26.680 --> 00:47:37.979
Greg K | Lido: But the point is that there might be a small fraction of the permissionless validators who cannot afford to bond for, for 2048.

274
00:47:37.980 --> 00:47:47.049
Greg K | Lido: So, essentially, what this enables is the smaller players that are using Lido's permissionless staking to

275
00:47:47.190 --> 00:47:49.509
Greg K | Lido: contribute to Ethereum decentralization.

276
00:47:49.510 --> 00:48:13.339
Greg K | Lido: to keep them inside the game. So they could afford now a small bond, perhaps very slightly higher than now, become 002, and also don't kicked out in the future when the attester size gap comes, which is currently on Hegota of the protocol. So it's basically saving the kind of most decentralized 5%, which is vulnerable.

277
00:48:13.340 --> 00:48:16.549
Greg K | Lido: For the future, like, changes coming.

278
00:48:16.810 --> 00:48:26.880
Greg K | Lido: And yeah, last, why check withizable timing, I think, is… I think it perfectly matches with the currently announced road map. I have a small screenshot on the related items.

279
00:48:26.880 --> 00:48:44.540
Greg K | Lido: But the target is at Hegota, which is… which is expected to be one year after Hegota, essentially. The fast finality will become feasible with 100 gate validators, so it will give enough time to have one year between this feature gets enabled.

280
00:48:44.540 --> 00:48:57.960
Greg K | Lido: And, the cap of number of validators being applied, so that both staking pools and validators have time to adjust, before getting kicked out due to this capping.

281
00:48:57.980 --> 00:49:13.569
Greg K | Lido: And also, as I said before, there are other future big concerns improvements that exist on the strawmap, and this EIP is not so complex, and it will make those changes, which are here for the protocol easier to occur in the future.

282
00:49:13.820 --> 00:49:26.359
Greg K | Lido: So, this is it. Yeah, there is also a thread in the mathematicians, there is also a PR open for, including this EIP in the Hegota Meta EIP, and yeah, happy to take any questions.

